    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n  <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\" />\n  <title>Space Complexity Demo</title>\n  <style>\n    body {\n      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n      margin: 2rem;\n      background: #f0f8ff;\n      color: #333;\n    }\n    h1 {\n      color: #2c3e50;\n    }\n    .container {\n      max-width: 700px;\n      margin: auto;\n      background: white;\n      padding: 1.5rem;\n      border-radius: 8px;\n      box-shadow: 0 8px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);\n    }\n    pre {\n      background: #272822;\n      color: #f8f8f2;\n      padding: 1rem;\n      border-radius: 6px;\n      overflow-x: auto;\n    }\n    button {\n      background-color: #2980b9;\n      color: white;\n      border: none;\n      padding: 0.6rem 1.2rem;\n      font-size: 1rem;\n      border-radius: 5px;\n      cursor: pointer;\n      margin-top: 1rem;\n    }\n    button:hover {\n      background-color: #3498db;\n    }\n    #output {\n      margin-top: 1rem;\n      padding: 1rem;\n      background: #ecf0f1;\n      border-radius: 6px;\n      font-family: monospace;\n      white-space: pre-wrap;\n      min-height: 80px;\n    }\n    .explanation {\n      margin-top: 1rem;\n      background-color: #dff0d8;\n      border-left: 5px solid #3c763d;\n      padding: 1rem;\n      border-radius: 4px;\n      color: #3c763d;\n    }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <div class=\"container\">\n    <h1>Space Complexity Demonstration</h1>\n    <p>\n      Space complexity is the amount of memory an algorithm needs relative to the input size.\n      Let's see this concept with two functions that calculate the <strong>sum of numbers from 1 to n</strong>:\n    </p>\n\n    <h2>Example 1: Iterative Approach (constant space)</h2>\n    <pre>\nfunction iterativeSum(n) {\n  let sum = 0;          // uses a fixed amount of space\n  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {\n    sum += i;\n  }\n  return sum;\n}\n    </pre>\n    <button id=\"btnIterative\">Run iterativeSum(1000000)</button>\n    <div id=\"outputIterative\"></div>\n\n    <h2>Example 2: Create Array and Reduce (linear space)</h2>\n    <pre>\nfunction arraySum(n) {\n  // creates an array of size n -> O(n) space\n  let arr = Array.from({length: n}, (_, i) => i + 1);\n  let sum = arr.reduce((acc, val) => acc + val, 0);\n  return sum;\n}\n    </pre>\n    <button id=\"btnArray\">Run arraySum(1000000)</button>\n    <div id=\"outputArray\"></div>\n\n    <div class=\"explanation\">\n      <h3>Explanation:</h3>\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>iterativeSum:</strong> Uses a constant amount of extra memory regardless of <code>n</code>. It only stores <code>sum</code> and <code>i</code>.</li>\n        <li><strong>arraySum:</strong> Creates an array of <code>n</code> elements, which uses memory proportional to <code>n</code> (linear space complexity).</li>\n      </ul>\n      <p>\n        So even though both compute the same result, their <strong>space complexity</strong> differs:\n      </p>\n      <ul>\n        <li><code>iterativeSum</code>: O(1) space</li>\n        <li><code>arraySum</code>: O(n) space</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <script>\n    function iterativeSum(n) {\n      let sum = 0;\n      for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {\n        sum += i;\n      }\n      return sum;\n    }\n\n    function arraySum(n) {\n      let arr = Array.from({length: n}, (_, i) => i + 1);\n      let sum = arr.reduce((acc, val) => acc + val, 0);\n      return sum;\n    }\n\n    const btnIterative = document.getElementById('btnIterative');\n    const outputIterative = document.getElementById('outputIterative');\n    btnIterative.addEventListener('click', () => {\n      outputIterative.textContent = 'Calculating...';\n      setTimeout(() => {\n        const n = 1000000;\n        const result = iterativeSum(n);\n        outputIterative.textContent = \n          `Result: ${result}\\n` +\n          `Memory used: Constant amount (only a few variables).\\n` +\n          `(Space Complexity: O(1))`;\n      }, 100);\n    });\n\n    const btnArray = document.getElementById('btnArray');\n    const outputArray = document.getElementById('outputArray');\n    btnArray.addEventListener('click', () => {\n      outputArray.textContent = 'Calculating...';\n      setTimeout(() => {\n        const n = 1000000;\n        const result = arraySum(n);\n        outputArray.textContent = \n          `Result: ${result}\\n` +\n          `Memory used: Array of length ${n} created.\\n` +\n          `(Space Complexity: O(n))`;\n      }, 100);\n    });\n  </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
